    "snippet": "While operating a UTV en route to deliver repair equipment to another UTV that had sustained a flat tire, the vehicle tipped onto its side. The operator attempted to ascend a...",
    "narrative": "While operating a UTV en route to deliver repair equipment to another UTV that had sustained a flat tire, the vehicle tipped onto its side. The operator attempted to ascend a hill in four-wheel drive. Upon attempting the climb and cresting the hill, the terrain proved to be uneven and more angled than it had appeared from below. This resulted in a lateral shift in the vehicle’s center of gravity, causing the UTV to tip onto its side.The rollover occurred at a low speed, and the operator—who was the sole occupant—was uninjured. The operator was properly restrained and wearing a helmet at the time of the incident. He was able to self-extricate and promptly notified Incident Command (ICP), reporting no injuries based on self-assessment.At the time of notification, only two personnel were present at ICP. The Incident Commander (IC) responded directly to the scene due to close proximity, and other resources being farther away, while the Medical Unit Leader (MEDL) remained at ICP to manage Incident within an Incident (IWI) responsibilities should there be a need.Upon arrival, the IC found that the operator had already righted the UTV. The operator continued to decline medical evaluation. No mechanical or operational issues were identified with the UTV.On-site discussion and education were provided regarding terrain conditions, specifically the instability of loose, sandy soil and its contribution to rollover risk. It was also noted that existing tire tracks indicated a previous successful ascent/descent via the same route without a reported or known incident",
    "immediateAction": "Immediate education included providing on-scene safety education to the UTV operator regarding the hazards associated with loose, shifting soil and its effect on vehicle stability specifically when paired with uneven terrain. Additionally, a broader safety briefing was scheduled for the next operational briefing to ensure all personnel assigned to the incident are aware of these risks, given the extensive use of UTVs on this fire.  In self-review the driver self-identified that had he walked the hill to view the other side prior to ascent he would have identified the hole and loose sand on his ascent path.",
