    "displayDate": "03/21/2026 18:00",
    "meta": "WV · P9EK7L26 · USFS",
    "state": "WV",
    "agency": "USFS",
    "localUnit": "",
    "factors": [
      "Equipment"
    ],
    "snippet": "On 3/21 the module leader, who was driving the engine, smelled an odor in the engine cab, he stated “something stinks” to the other crew members riding in the engine. The other...",
    "narrative": "On 3/21 the module leader, who was driving the engine, smelled an odor in the engine cab, he stated “something stinks” to the other crew members riding in the engine. The other crew members stated they could smell a faint odor as well resembling a dead rodent like.On 3/22 the crew was working on a prescribed burn. Crew members smelt the odor again and said it smelt like a dead animal. They said the smell was faint and inconsistent throughout the day. Crewmembers checked the engine compartment, and all cargo compartments on the engine, nothing obvious was detected. Later that evening after the burn, crewmembers were experiencing scratchy throats and nose bleeds.On 3/23 the crew was enroute to prep a prescribed burn unit. The smell was stronger than previous days and more consistent throughout the day. The driver said the smell seemed to be coming through the diver side vent. Crew members saw what they thought was a small puff of smoke but thought it was just some steam coming off the exhaust since it was raining. As they were returning to town, they saw smoke from the engine compartment. They pulled to the side of the road, opened the hood and smoke was coming out of the engine area. The crew member who opened the hood said the smoke “hit him in the face.” Once the smoke dissipated, they looked over the engine compartment to attempt to diagnose the problem. They did not have cell coverage and once the smoke stopped, they decided to drive the engine into town and parked it at the hotel. They contacted the FDO and notified them of the situation with the engine. After arriving back at the hotel, crewmembers started to experience headaches, felt disoriented and had a “sandpaper” feeling in their throats. They notified the FDO who went to the hotel. After speaking with the module leader, the decision was made to transport all 8 folks to the local hospital. Six crew members were evaluated at the hospital. The FDO called the local dispatch to order a Hospital Liaison, but none was available locally. Notifications were made to the local unit Forest Supervisor, Forest Safety Officer and Forest FMO as well as the home unit and R9 Duty Officer. A Care Team was established consisting of R9 CAP Coordinator, WO on call Duty Officer & Job Corp Risk Management. After examination, the diagnosis was exposure to sulfuric acid fumes and carbon monoxide. All crew members were treated and released from hospital that night with no work restrictions.",
    "immediateAction": "The next morning the FDO meet with the crew at the hotel. Crewmembers were still experiencing symptoms such as coughing and light-headed-ness. The decision was made to keep the crew at the hotel for the day to rest and complete paperwork. The following day the crew leader spoke to the FDO and said the crew was good to return to work. The FDO placed the engine out of service and arrangements were made for it to be towed to the dealership for repairs. For the next few days crew members continued to experience headaches and some fatigue.Everyone involved appreciated the immense support from local, Region 9, Region 6 and WO staff.Lessons LearnedWhen something seems out of the ordinary, don’t minimize it. Small things can become big issues if ignored. Even though daily checks were conducted, and the crew investigated the smell, the engine should have been taken in for professional service. Once the smoke was detected, the engine should have been parked and a tow requested.Individuals were initially hesitant to speak up with symptoms and didn’t feel there was a need to seek medical evaluation. Once crew members started talking, it became known that multiple folks were experiencing similar symptoms and medical care was sought.Focus should always be on patient safety and getting prompt treatment. Don’t delay treatment to complete paperwork.The engine was not in daily use and was assigned to the crew when they arrived on forest. If vehicles have not been operated for long durations, ensure thorough checks are done and consider taking them in for service.",
    "mgmtLevel": "N/A",
    "task": "RX Prep",
    "resources": "ENGB,FFT1, FFT2",
