    "snippet": "Our radios went down on Saturday, 03/28/2026. We are not certain of the exact time, but we believe the outage occurred later in the afternoon. At the time, we were conducting a...",
    "narrative": "Our radios went down on Saturday, 03/28/2026. We are not certain of the exact time, but we believe the outage occurred later in the afternoon. At the time, we were conducting a controlled burn on the Lakeside District and using a Type 3 helicopter for PSD work. Communications were stable because we were operating through the Porter Mountain substation.On the forest side, the Greens Peak mountaintop site went down; however, we were still able to communicate with ground resources through other substations. The larger concern with Greens Peak being down is that it not only impacts forest communications, but it also disrupts National Flight Following, which becomes non-functional when Greens Peak is offline. A Safecom will also be submitted regarding the incident.Our radio technician was notified Monday morning, and a ticket was submitted the same day. After discussing the situation with him, he believes the issue is on the network side, as that has been the cause of the last two outages within the past two weeks. This appears to be a recurring problem happening once a week or so.I have significant concerns for the safety of our ground personnel and our aviators if this issue is not addressed promptly. A permanent fix needs to be prioritized, as we cannot afford repeated radio failures at any time of year—especially with fire season approaching.",
    "immediateAction": "Notified our radio tech and submitted a ticket. The radios are still down. We contacted our neighboring dispatch centers and asked them to monitor our national Flight Follwing / Air guard radio traffic. Notified all of the Apache-Sitgreaves personnel about greens peak being down and utilizing other radio substations or cell phone if needed.",
