    "agency": "USFS",
    "localUnit": "Sacramento Ranger Dixtrict, Lincoln National Forest",
    "factors": [
      "Communications",
      "Human Factors"
    ],
    "snippet": "Around mid-day of 02/28/2026, during the firing and holding phase of a prescribed burn, radio communication was lost with dispatch due to a faulty system. Operations continued...",
    "narrative": "Around mid-day of 02/28/2026, during the firing and holding phase of a prescribed burn, radio communication was lost with dispatch due to a faulty system. Operations continued via Starlink, had that failed there would have been no communications whatsoever since we were operating in an area without cell coverage. My main concern is not that we operated without radio comms, it's that we have had TERRIBLE radio comms since I started on this forest 16 years ago. Couple that with the fact that we have a dispatch center that is managed by someone who has never been a dispatcher, and an IA floor full of dispatchers that have never been a firefighter or have any kind of operational background in fire, and we've got ourselves a recipe for disaster and it's only a matter of time before something bad happens. Instead of waiting for that day, it seems like we could be more proactive in having our radio system PROPERLY looked at by qualified personnel. We have a radio tech on the forest, and he'll give us every explanation and excuse as to why it's not working. The excuses and finger pointing have gone on for years and we are all fed up with it. This is extremely unsafe, especially as we are moving into yet another fire season. Not sure what it takes to get a functional radio system and technician, as well as qualified personnel at dispatch, but we would sure like to know and have it implemented as soon as possible.",
    "immediateAction": "There wasn't much that could be done in this situation to remedy it, the burn boss and trainee told us all that we had lost radio comms with dispatch but that we would continue working using Starlink for comms. So, everyone kept working.",
    "mgmtLevel": "N/A",
