    "snippet": "The Federal Communication Center in San Bernardino serves as an interagency dispatch center responsible for coordinating all-hazard responses. The facility is managed by the U.S....",
    "narrative": "The Federal Communication Center in San Bernardino serves as an interagency dispatch center responsible for coordinating all-hazard responses. The facility is managed by the U.S. Forest Service (USFS) San Bernardino. For several months, the building has been without primary power. When the backup generator ran out of oil, the USFS employee responsible for its maintenance was on leave, resulting in a complete failure of backup power and loss of all communication capabilities with field units.During this outage, the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) was actively managing multiple medical incidents with partner agencies and lost communication with dispatch. Field units were only able to coordinate responses through a relay unit with cell coverage. Despite these challenges, responders successfully managed both incidents, including airlifting one patient with significant injuries to a trauma center.USFS leadership has been aware of the ongoing power issues for several months but has taken no proactive measures to resolve them. The backup generator’s failure due to lack of oil indicates inadequate maintenance and reliability. This situation creates a serious employee and public safety risk, potentially contributing to severe injury or loss of life.",
    "immediateAction": "The Federal Communication Center in San Bernardino serves as an interagency dispatch center responsible for coordinating all-hazard responses. The facility is managed by the U.S. Forest Service (USFS) San Bernardino. For several months, the building has been without primary power. When the backup generator ran out of oil, the USFS employee responsible for its maintenance was on leave, resulting in a complete failure of backup power and loss of all communication capabilities with field units.During this outage, the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) was actively managing multiple medical incidents with partner agencies and lost communication with dispatch. Field units were only able to coordinate responses through a relay unit with cell coverage. Despite these challenges, responders successfully managed both incidents, including airlifting one patient with significant injuries to a trauma center.USFS leadership has been aware of the ongoing power issues for several months but has taken no proactive measures to resolve them. The backup generator’s failure due to lack of oil indicates inadequate maintenance and reliability. This situation creates a serious employee and public safety risk, potentially contributing to severe injury or loss of life.",
