    "snippet": "After many months and even years of the YOSE ECC switch to the new dispatch center, communications between field resources and dispatchers in the ECC has been greatly diminished...",
    "narrative": "After many months and even years of the YOSE ECC switch to the new dispatch center, communications between field resources and dispatchers in the ECC has been greatly diminished due to the elimination of a vital command channel. The fire command channel labeled FIRE DIRECT was used daily by both field personnel, resources in stations, and dispatchers in the ECC to effectively communicate. While the transition to the new center wasn’t a surprise and the telecom shop was well aware of the changes coming to the radio frequencies, that information wasn’t relayed to the fire resources until just minutes before the official switch over was to occur. The timing of this information came a very inconvenient time due to the fact there were multiple fire units out on active wildfires, along with the park helicopter being utilized to support those fire fighting actions. FIRE DIRECT has/had been the primary channel used in many areas throughout Yosemite National Park to communicate direct with YOSE ECC. This channel was removed for further use with no warning and created a large gap in our communication between the ECC and fire personnel.",
    "immediateAction": "Upon hearing of this change to the fire channels. I immediately sent out an urgent email to all fire personnel explaining the situation and asking them to stop using FIRE DIRECT and to use other fire channels to communicate with the ECC. I also asked for those directions be relayed out to personnel in the field. This was done to ensure that our fire resources were able to effectively communicate with ECC with out having the use of the FIRE DIRECT channel.",
