    "snippet": "While assigned to an extended attack fire and performing normal duties traveling between areas of the fire on a gravel road, with washboards and rocks, the GPS tracking unit fell...",
    "narrative": "While assigned to an extended attack fire and performing normal duties traveling between areas of the fire on a gravel road, with washboards and rocks, the GPS tracking unit fell from behind the dashboard and impeded the brake pedal from being depressed. Vehicle speeds were less than 20mph at the time and haven't exceeded over 35mph for the duration of the time spent on the incident.Operator had to take eyes off the road, lean down, and grab GPS unit from behind brake pedal while trying to coast to a stop. Upon further inspection from the ENGB, the GPS unit had only been secured with 1 zip tie that had loosened from the bumpy road. GPS unit was installed within the past 18 months and similar was found on a new T6 Engine which had the installation done within the past 2 months.",
    "immediateAction": "GPS unit was lodged further into dashboard off to a far side and purposely entangled in wires to 'better secure' it.No further action was taken to secure due to anti-tamper alarm going off.Incident was reported to Safety for the CIMT during briefing, Home Forest Safety Officer, Home Forest Fleet Manger, and Home Unit Duty Officers.Recommended fix would be strong glue strips, velcro strips, rubber cement.Highly encourage to not continue to use zip ties due to the nature of the roads that we drive daily.",
