    "snippet": "WACCC dispatch operations have been impacted by multiple infrastructure failures: Power Outages causing complete loss of lighting within the dispatch floor. Phone and Network...",
    "narrative": "WACCC dispatch operations have been impacted by multiple infrastructure failures: Power Outages causing complete loss of lighting within the dispatch floor. Phone and Network Interruptions, regional wide outages and recently including a  network disconnection tied to the Gifford Pinchot Forest Supervisor’s Office (GPF SO) server upgrade to Lumen for 987 but excluding WACCCDispatch continuity is critical to firefighters and public safety. Infrastructure failures create unsafe working conditions and reduce the ability of dispatchers to coordinate effective response. A local power outage caused all lights within dispatch to fail. An electrician was able to partially restore power, returning approximately half of the lights for a two week period but all lights have failed.Dispatcher safety and efficiency were reduced, situational awareness was compromised, and resource response could have been delayed. Manual logs and radios were required to maintain operations.  Phone interruptions further limited dispatcher ability to coordinate with duty officers and cooperators. During the same period, WACCC was disconnected from the GPF SO network after IT upgraded the SO infrastructure but failed to update WACCC’s connection. IT records incorrectly listed dispatch as having moved into the SO. As a result, WACCC remained on AT&T while the SO migrated, creating a significant outage. IT has since identified and corrected the discrepancy, but this highlighted systemic dependency and documentation issues.",
    "immediateAction": "Power and lightsDispatch operations required temporary desk lamps, portable lighting, and workspace adjustments to continue functioning until Facilities could make permanent repairs. This created physical safety hazards (slips, trips, eye strain) and degraded the working environment. NetworkContacted CEC and TMACO TMACO was able to cancel the disconnect order issued but the WACCC network is still operating on 20m circuit.",
