    "meta": "CA · USFS",
    "state": "CA",
    "agency": "USFS",
    "localUnit": "",
    "factors": [
      "Equipment"
    ],
    "snippet": "Checking into the Green fire, we noticed the center console screws that were holding down the radios, lights and siren controllers and other panels kept falling out from our...",
    "narrative": "Checking into the Green fire, we noticed the center console screws that were holding down the radios, lights and siren controllers and other panels kept falling out from our driving on the road, Hwy 299, to main ICP at Fenders Ferry Rd. We checked in at camp to start the process of being on the fire and at this time the FEO started to put the screws back into the correct areas and tighten them down. We drove about 1/2 mile from ICP to ground support and the screws were loose once again. When we got to ground support, I asked them if there was anything they could do to secure the center console plates and electronics. The FMI grabbed the whole center console and lifted half the console up off the ground and instantly red tagged us for the center console not being secure to the floor.After some time and talking with the other ground support mechanics they realized that the strapping had broken free from the floor mount base screws in a spot on the bracket that would be a weak point. The strapping broke on the passenger side bottom, front and back, of the center console that attaches to the bolts that hold the seat down. These brackets have a spot in them that allows for different mounting options which is where the failure happened.",
    "immediateAction": "The strategy was to reinforce the metal strapping and re secure the center console. The mechanic did some great welding and strengthened the metal support strapping to get us back into full operation. After the center console was secured, we put all the electronics back in and all the screws that were not holding are now holding well and still in place. We opted to have a custom-made bracket made using the old bracket to reattach the center console the way it was originally designed for this apparatus build. Once the welding of additional metal was completed the bracket was reinstalled into its correct placement and tightened the seat mounting bolts down. The console is stronger and more secure as we were able to complete our full assignment on unpaved rough dirt roads on the Green fire.",
    "mgmtLevel": "1",
    "task": "",
