    "snippet": "27th June 2025: During the evening of the 27th while managing a type three incident BLM Fire assets lost communication with Northern Colorado Interagency Dispatch Center (NOCO)....",
    "narrative": "27th June 2025: During the evening of the 27th while managing a type three incident BLM Fire assets lost communication with Northern Colorado Interagency Dispatch Center (NOCO). At that time I called the BLM Colorado Telecommunication Manager. He was already on the phone (On-Call) with NOCO Center Manager trying to figure out what the next steps were. It was determined that the BLM equipment at the old Craig Dispatch Center was fully functional, and most of the Craig USFS ROIP network-controlled radios were down. That evening we made sure that every aircraft was back in Craig, and all firefighters were off the line for the evening. The IC made sure he had cell phone coverage just in case there was an IWI in camp. Plans were made to man the old Craig Dispatch center in the morning if still needed. The breakdown in communication highlights significant risks that can compromise both the safety of individuals on the fire line and the efficiency of firefighting operations. Addressing these vulnerabilities is essential for ensuring a safe working environment during wildland fire incidents.",
    "immediateAction": "28th June 0600: I came into the old Craig Interagency Dispatch Center and determined that NOCO Dispatch was still mostly inoperable, so I then began operating a BLM console at Craig while the telecommunication manager was working with the DFPC IT tech at NOCO to find a work-around. The BLM cellular Go-Kit console was brought on-line at NOCO to provide control of the seven BLM radios out of Craig. Most of the USFS radios controlled out of Craig, were still down due to them also being controlled over the USFS data network. The outage is estimated to be caused by a failure/degradation of the USFS ROIP data network. This is the second time in three weeks that we have had a major communications outage with NOCO Dispatch. It is our recommendation that the USFS data network be hardened with redundant paths to key radio infrastructure.",
    "mgmtLevel": "3",
    "task": "Agency Duty Officer",
    "resources": "Northern Colorado Interagency Dispatch Center",
