    "id": "old-53927",
    "safeNetId": "20250429-0002",
    "name": "Prescribed fire drip torch fuel leak resulting in burn Injury",
    "isoDate": "2025-04-24",
    "displayDate": "04/24/2025 14:00",
    "meta": "AK · AK-MID-250001 · BLM",
    "state": "AK",
    "agency": "BLM",
    "localUnit": "Alaska Fire Service/Military Zone",
    "factors": [
      "Equipment",
      "Human Factors"
    ],
    "snippet": "During pre-implementation for annual prescribed fire operations on the Donnally Training Area a cache order was issued for equipment and supplies. This included an order for 15...",
    "narrative": "During pre-implementation for annual prescribed fire operations on the Donnally Training Area a cache order was issued for equipment and supplies. This included an order for 15 new drip torches. Once Rx implementation began, the prescribed fire personnel noted and spoke at some length in AARs and safety briefings how the new torches seemed more difficult to 'flip' and correctly seal. It was assumed that this was because they were new and not broken in. As a precaution all prescribed fire personnel were directed to not let cooperator resources (local military Fire Department) fill torches without supervision. However during firing operations personal torch management was allowed with oversight. During afternoon blackline operations on the Texas NE unit on the DTAE 3 burners were assigned to blackline an area with a thick brushy component. I was the Firing Boss and also operating a UTV with a water tank to create a 'wetline' for an indirect line to exclude a think timber stringer. I was also carrying full torches to support the igniters. We were tying in a 2 track to a pond to exclude the timber. My trainee was working with a torch to gain depth interior. There was an inexperienced cooperator assigned to the second interior burner of the blackline edge. The Burner on the edge of the blackline (Firefighter with 5+ years experience but new to Alaska Rx tactics) needed a new torch. I stopped the UTV in the Brush and flipped a new torch for her. I was watching the inexperienced structure firefighter behind her to make sure he did not outpace us in the thick brush and I was distracted by this. When I flipped the torch it threaded all the way down but there was some resistance as it threaded. I did not key in on this, or double check the torch seal. I handed the torch to the edge lighter and continued to drive in the UTV and progress the wetline. The edge lighter continued for several minutes and noticed her lower right pantleg was on fire. She attempted to swat it out without success. My trainee instructed her to 'Stop, drop and roll.' she dropped her torch and successfully extinguished the flames. She then continued to burn. I had tied the wetline into the pond and turned around to watch the ignitions. At this point, I observed the edge igniter tip her torch and saw fuel dripping from the seal. I yelled for her to stop. She exited the firing operation into the green and we then resealed the torch correctly. When we tied the burn into the pond, she told me she had burned her leg. I immediately put her in the UTV and we exited the fire area. I exposed her leg and observed a palm sized area of red skin, with a 3 inch by 2 inch area of peeled skin in the center. She stated she was fine and requested to keep going. As a trained EMT I made the decision to transport her to the nearest clinic by ground and seek treatment after washing and dressing the burn with a dry sterile bandage. The burn was categorized as 'superficial' by the physician and return to full duty was authorized. She was able to continue work the following day without much discomfort.",
    "immediateAction": "All torches were inspected and several were flagged that were more difficult to thread correctly. These torches were discontinued from service. All Prescribed fire personnel discussed situational awareness, checking torches for leaks before use and possible actions to identify faulty equipment. It was also discussed that there might be a possibility the new generation/manufacturer of cache issued torches could be more finicky, or faulty. It was decided to file a safe net to track trends not only in human factors and (lack of) situational awareness, but potential (commonly used) equipment failure.",
    "mgmtLevel": "2",
    "task": "Rx Operations/Blackline",
    "resources": "Crew",
