    "snippet": "On about April 1 aircraft operating within the Southeast Arizona Zone response area reported they could not hear Tucson Interagency Dispatch over a Forest Service National Flight...",
    "narrative": "On about April 1 aircraft operating within the Southeast Arizona Zone response area reported they could not hear Tucson Interagency Dispatch over a Forest Service National Flight Following radio repeater. Aircraft reported transmissions heard from Tucson Dispatch over a second Bureau of Land Management flight following repeater were either barely audible or not understandable. Both repeaters normally provide clear radio communications between aircraft and the dispatch center. Command frequencies were/are available as a backup for flight tracking, but their use adds aircraft communications to potentially busy Administrative and Fire frequencies.Since Apr 1, additional radio communications from Tucson Dispatch over the local Forest Service National FF repeater have intermittently not been heard by aircraft. Radio communications technicians have been trouble-shooting the problem and have not been able to determine a cause. A potential complication to remedying the radio issue is replacement parts are scarce.National Flight Following is critical to interagency wildfire aviation operations. It is used for flight tracking of hundreds of aircraft, timely communication of incident and airspace information, and the redirection of aircraft to priority fires. It is essential that the system be maintained and upgraded in the best possible manner.",
    "immediateAction": "Identified use of local Command Admin Frequencies for aircraft communications until the National Flight Following radio issue gets resolved. Reported the issue through the FS CIO system.",
