    "snippet": "While preparing for ignition operations on Div R/S on the Middle Fork, There was a yellow medical on an adjacent Div. The medical involved an individual who had fallen and broken...",
    "narrative": "While preparing for ignition operations on Div R/S on the Middle Fork, There was a yellow medical on an adjacent Div. The medical involved an individual who had fallen and broken his/her leg and torn their knee joint up. There was emergency traffic declared and the command net ordered cleared. About 10 minutes into the Medical a second emergency was declared on Div R/S involving a UAS module. The module had lost connection with it's aircraft and had presumed it crashed. The UAS was doing IR on a section of fire line that had been burned the previous shift. The air quality was poor and there were no aircraft flying due to visibility caused by smoke. The drone crash was deemed an emergency and proceeded to override the medical that involved an actual human being. There were multiple transmissions on Command about the crash and instructions given for locating and securing the site. Again, there were no aircraft flying and since it was an Unmanned aircraft it should have not been an emergency that warranted communications to be interrupted on the actual emergency that was in progress.",
    "immediateAction": "The only actions that were taken by me was to point out the absurdity of the situation in general, and to voice my concerns as a CRWB that the PEOPLE always come first. Also to remind them that they were currently interrupting an ongoing medical that involved a possibly seriously injured firefighter. I was informed it was mandated by the FAA to declare the emergency due to the unknown location of the drone and its hazard to other aircraft. That is fine, but there were no other aircraft flying due to visibility. The incident should have been handled by phone or on the tac channel for the division.",
    "mgmtLevel": "2",
