    "factors": [
      "Communications",
      "Human Factors"
    ],
    "snippet": "This incident utilized Business Itinerant radio frequencies (151.5050, 151.5125, 151.7000, 151.7600, 154.5275, 158.4000, 158.4075) for Command and Tactical Channels during the...",
    "narrative": "This incident utilized Business Itinerant radio frequencies (151.5050, 151.5125, 151.7000, 151.7600, 154.5275, 158.4000, 158.4075) for Command and Tactical Channels during the fire response. These frequencies are not designated for public safety use. Due to their nationwide licensing by the FCC, they are difficult to track. A business or radio rental company from another state may hold a license for these frequencies and legally operate them anywhere in the country. This complicates the process of determining potential interference from properly licensed entities. It is common for these frequencies to be programmed into rental radios for special events, such as concerts, fairs, community gatherings, private security operations, drive-thru restaurants, and department stores. While no radio frequency interference was experienced or reported during this incident, I believe it is only a matter of time before significant interference occurs.",
    "immediateAction": "I was not assigned to this incident and became aware of the issue only after the fact.Type 3 Incident Management Teams (IMTs), which are rapidly deployed to coordinate the transition from initial to extended attack, require quickly deployable communications equipment that travels with them. These IMTs do not have the luxury of waiting for radio communications equipment to be shipped. As a result, many carry their own repeaters and radio equipment. These same IMTs have attempted to use National Interoperability Field Operations Guide (NIFOG) frequencies (e.g., VTAC12, VTAC36, etc.). However, when multiple incidents are occurring within the same region or state, and several IMTs are deployed using the same NIFOG frequencies, interference becomes a significant issue.The Incident Management Teams are not acting with intentional disregard by using Business Itinerant radio frequencies. They recognized a problem with multiple incidents using the same NIFOG frequencies and implemented a solution by using Business Itinerant frequencies for repeated Command channels and simplex Tactical channels. However, despite these efforts, a significant safety concern still exists.",
    "mgmtLevel": "3",
    "task": "Communications",
    "resources": "",
