    "snippet": "07/17/2024 A grass fire was ignited in a designated impact area as a result of soldier training activities (aerial gunnery). An initial attack response was initiated by the Fort...",
    "narrative": "07/17/2024 A grass fire was ignited in a designated impact area as a result of soldier training activities (aerial gunnery). An initial attack response was initiated by the Fort Hunter Liggett Fire Department, including 1 Chief Officer (Deputy Fire Chief), 1 type III engine, 1 Patrol unit, and one support vehicle. The first unit on scene was the Deputy Fire Chief. I will describe the sequence of events chronologically: 2004-Fire reported, response initiated by 'Liggett' dispatch 2008-Deputy Fire Chief at scene, additional F.D. resources arrive shortly after 2024-Deputy Fire Chief establishes Stony I.C., advises 'Liggett' that back burn operations have begun, requests two type III engines from Cal Fire 2203-Stony I.C. Advises back burn operations are tied in (final acreage not provided at this time but final size was determined to be 1500 acres) 2209-Cal Fire engines are released 2253-Deputy Fire Chief terminates Stony I.C., returns to quarters 2304-All resources off incident and back in quarters 2311-Deputy Fire Chief advises 'Liggett', flames will still be visible, interior only 07/18/2024 0830-1 Lieutenant and 1 Firefighter directed to check fire in Patrol 8852 0850-Patrol 8852 arrives at scene and begins patrolling the fires edge, determine that lines have held, and all smokes are burning interior. Some limited mop up work is performed from the roads to eliminate threats to the line. No interior (off the road) mop-up work is performed due to the unexploded ordnance potential and the signs posted around the burn area. Entire burn is inside a restricted area with a known UXO risk. The past practice is to not leave the main roads inside these areas to mitigate UXO risk. 1030 (approximately) - Patrol 8852 returns to quarters, LT informs Deputy Fire Chief that the fire looks okay and is inside existing lines. 1100 (approximately)- Deputy Fire Chief calls LT by cell. Informs the LT that himself and the Fire Chief have driven around the fires edge. They are dissatisfied with the quality of the mop up performed and report smokes around the fire near a bridge. Deputy Fire Chief directs the LT to return to the fire with the Firefighter, utilizing a Patrol and a water tender. Informs the LT that the areas of concern are a burning bridge timber near a water crossing and a large tree that has fallen near the 'dozer off-loading site'. LT states that fire is in a known UXO hazard area and has concerns about mop up operations off the roadside. Deputy Fire Chief instructs LT to conduct mop up 100' inside the burn. Despite the availability of two additional F.D. engines, only two individuals are assigned to return for mop up. 1130 (approximately)-LT and FF return to fire with WT8842 and Patrol 8852. 1150 (approximately)-WT8842 and Patrol 8852 arrive back at the fire. Higher temperatures and lower relative humidity have led to an increase in the visible number of smokes. Both units work in conjunction to identify priorities. The tree burning near the 'dozer off-loading area' is located. It is well within the UXO area with warning signs clearly visible in close proximity to the tree. The Deputy Fire Chief and the Fire Chief would have seen the multiple warning signs during their site visit. LT and FF discuss the assignment. They agree it may be better for them to complete the assignment than risk the chance of having the Deputy Fire Chief delegate the mission to lesser experienced employees. The LT and FF proceed to conduct limited mop up operations for the next few hours. The areas of concern and visible smokes within 100' of the line are mopped up per the Deputy Fire Chiefs instructions. 1430-LT and FF return to quarters with water tender and Patrol vehicle. 1450-LT and FF arrive back at quarters and re outfit both vehicles. 1530 (approximately)-LT provides debrief to Deputy Fire Chief. He asks again about the safety concerns with mopping up 100' inside UXO areas. Deputy Fire Chief states that he never instructed the LT perform the activity. The policy of the Army is to not allow anyone to enter restricted areas that have UXO potential. The Deputy Fire Chief knowingly made an unsafe work assignment violating multiple established work practices.",
    "immediateAction": "Photos were taken as well as a GPS track to document the activities.",
