    "factors": [
      "Equipment"
    ],
    "snippet": "In the afternoon of 7/15 several phones in the Columbia Cascade Dispatch Center Initial Attack Floor and Expanded Dispatch Office ceased normal functions. We were able to...",
    "narrative": "In the afternoon of 7/15 several phones in the Columbia Cascade Dispatch Center Initial Attack Floor and Expanded Dispatch Office ceased normal functions. We were able to piecemeal a functional set up back together by relocating working phones from unstaffed desks to staffed desks. In the immediate aftermath of the initial outage we reached out direct to a CIO IT staff member who has been assisting us with other ongoing phone issues. The individual was unable to assist in fixing or even identifying what the issue was and a ticket was submitted to CHD and requested to be elevated, on the evening of 7/15. The ticket was picked up by the after hours IT support and one individual in dispatch spent 2 hours on the phone with the help desk trying to identify and mitigate the issues, with no resolution. At this point only 30% of the phones were functional, roughly 10 out of 30 phones, and the day shift turned the center over to night shift for overnight staffing. The following day, 7/16, started with the phones in much the same state as they were left. As the morning progressed the situation continued to deteriorate with phone calls not reliably coming in at all by around noon. At this point we had 3 new smoke reports of potential wildfires in our zone, a medical incident on one of the forests we serve, a T1 IMT engaged in a large extended attack fire, and no phone communications. We were able to activate 6 emergency cell phones and several government owned cell phones and disseminate phone numbers to the local staff we support and as many local county 911 centers as we could. By this point the office only had 1 functional phone, no call waiting, and no ability to transfer calls as they came in. Additionally the structure of the building is not conducive to cell coverage and calls frequently are not connected, with no notification of a missed call, and calls are dropped regularly, making the emergency cell phone continuation of operations plan that much more tenuous. In the afternoon of 7/16 the network appeared to show degradation as well with intelligence web pages and online dispatching programs not loading properly, though intermittent functionality remains. The situation presented, and is continuing to present, serious safety concerns with the inability to communicate with outside entities including field going resources, EMS personnel and dispatch centers, aviation bases, and any number of other entity that contacts us via phone. Additionally there were/are red flag warnings in effect for multiple weather zones within our dispatch zone for abundant lighting, high temps, and low RH, for 7/16 and 7/17 adding to the potential for numerous missed reports of new starts leading to the unnecessary loss of resources, property, and life/safety.",
    "immediateAction": "Reached out direct to CIO IT staff member who has been assisting with ongoing phone issues. Submitted ticket to CHD, and requested it be elevated. Requested ticket be elevated again the following day. Reached out to the Regional Risk Management Officer after no resolution and deteriorating phone and network conditions.",
