    "meta": "WA · USFS",
    "state": "WA",
    "agency": "USFS",
    "localUnit": "Okanogan Wenatchee",
    "factors": [
      "Equipment"
    ],
    "snippet": "New style jerry cans for Mark 3 operation:We were tasked with structure protection on the Pioneer Fire / Prince Creek. We set up 2 pumping platforms to facilitate the task - upon...",
    "narrative": "New style jerry cans for Mark 3 operation:We were tasked with structure protection on the Pioneer Fire / Prince Creek. We set up 2 pumping platforms to facilitate the task - upon performance checks we noticed that we were having problems with pumps cutting out. Upon trouble shooting and identifying the contributing factor, we discovered that the new style jerry cans with the plug in port on the bottom right broad side of the can was sliding out slightly, but enough to cavitate the priming bulb and choke gase to the pump. We had two pumping platforms that had the exact same issue and identified that this could be more of a systematic issue. The reason that we feel that this potentially could be a foundational problem is that it takes about 5 minutes of operation before the pumps starts sputtering out. During an emergency and if not identified this would be a contributing problem.",
    "immediateAction": "We fixed the problem by using flagging akin to teflon tape around a pipe fitting. This seemed to be a short fix and resolved the problem.For Crews working with these styles of jerry cans, it appears that the pumps become flooded and there is a lot of time spent trying to address the problem if it is unknown.The pressure fitting from the gas line (priming bulb) to the jerry can on these style do not fit properly and the hose backs out of the port very slightly but enough to cut the gas. This happened on both pumping platforms with the exact same style jerry can. Sorry no pictures of the can- I reported this to the field Safety Officer with the hopes that the issue would be elevated.",
    "mgmtLevel": "1",
    "task": "Structure Protection",
    "resources": "Wildland Fire Module 1",
