    "state": "NM",
    "agency": "USFS",
    "localUnit": "Lincoln National Forest, Smokey Bear Range District",
    "factors": [
      "Human Factors"
    ],
    "snippet": "Local resources assigned to the Blue 2 BAER team and local resources assisting the BAER effort were denied travel authorization because they were in the local commuting area....",
    "narrative": "Local resources assigned to the Blue 2 BAER team and local resources assisting the BAER effort were denied travel authorization because they were in the local commuting area. This created a safety risk for employees who were required to travel early mornings to attend 6 am briefings at ICP and/or the BAER work area rather than stay on site in hotels like other team members. The increased risk comes from driving during the early morning when elk and other wildlife pose a danger and also traveling at dark at the end of a 12 hour shift. In other words, some BAER team members were allowed to stay on site with travel authorized and other team members had their travel authorization denied and had to travel from their home units to Ruidoso each day. This misapplication of the policy increased the safety risk to employees by requiring off-hours travel during an emergency.Denying local resources per diem during an emergency because they are in local commuting area does not follow national guidance from the Chief in a letter on 3/1/24 titled:Forest Service Travel and Lodging Guidance for Incident Response and Emergency Fuels and Health Treatments for the 21 Priority Landscapes and 250 Firesheds for Calendar Year 2024The letter states that:Per Diem Within 50 Miles of the Duty Station Due to Emergency Conditions Per diem for temporary duty travel (TDY) within the local travel area may only be provided when warranted by emergency conditions (7 U.S.C 2228). Emergency conditions may include wildfire, hurricane, or other disaster response and support that would endanger a traveler's health or safety if the individual were to return to their duty station or residence. The traveler should attempt to obtain pre-authorization whenever possible. However, the primary concern is for the traveler's safety and the agency may grant post-travel.Requests for travel authorization were denied by the local unit and the issue was raised by both the BAER team and members of the IMT during a meeting on 6/12/24.",
    "immediateAction": "Policy clarification was requested from the WO and presented to the forest.",
    "mgmtLevel": "1",
    "task": "local BAER resources travel",
    "resources": "BAER resources assigned to the BAER team from the local unit (Lincoln NF)",
