    "name": "USFS-R5-SQF Forest Radio Problems",
    "isoDate": "2024-06-07",
    "displayDate": "06/07/2024 10:00",
    "meta": "CA · USFS",
    "state": "CA",
    "agency": "USFS",
    "localUnit": "Sequoia National Forest",
    "factors": [
      "Communications",
      "Equipment"
    ],
    "snippet": "When dispatchers are talking on SQF Ch. 2 (Rx 169.9000, Tx 165.7000) and SQF Ch. 4 (Rx 170.5500, Tx 166.0000) simultaneously, the radios cancel each other out causing the radios...",
    "narrative": "When dispatchers are talking on SQF Ch. 2 (Rx 169.9000, Tx 165.7000) and SQF Ch. 4 (Rx 170.5500, Tx 166.0000) simultaneously, the radios cancel each other out causing the radios to walk on each other and both transmissions to become garbled. Radio transmissions get cut off causing communication issues between field units and dispatch. This could result in critical communications between dispatch and field units being disrupted to where this could result in employee injuries during fire operations, law enforcement activities and FPO public contacts.During an Initial Attack of the 155 Fire, we had a medical aid of an agency employee on a neighboring district. Both incidents were critical. The agency employee was suffering with what we at a later identified to be heat exhaustion while hiking in remote rugged terrain. At the same time as the medical incident, the 155 Fire had structure threat. Upon arriving on scene, the 155 Air Attack requested a no divert on air tankers due to threat to life and property.  In late 2022, we moved our dispatch center from its previous location to the newly built SQF Supervisor's Office across town. Since the move, we have had a several radio issues. One identified issue is that we cannot transmit on SQF Ch. 2 and SQF Ch. 4 at the same time because they walk on each other and both traffic become garbled. During the medical incident and 155 Fire, it took multiple radio calls to make out traffic with the fire resources and with the agency medical traffic. This issue has been reported to the SQF radio technicians and they attempted to reconfigure the wiring of the antennas in an attempt to provide more separation between the two antennas.",
    "immediateAction": "Until further notice we have moved the command channel for Initial Attack responses in the Interagency Area around Lake Isabella to the BLM channel – see below. Response Areas to change command channel: Lake Isabella, Weldon, Havilah, Democrat, Granite, and Adelaide.CND CH 4 RX 169.7750TX163.0250Tone 5 around Lake IsabellaTone 3 in the Lower Kern CanyonFor SQF daily traffic, resume normal usage on SQF Ch.2/ SQF Ch.4In addition, the SQF Radio Technicians are working to find a long-term solution to this problem.",
    "mgmtLevel": "N/A",
    "task": "Radio User",
    "resources": "All Field Units",
    "incidentType": [
      "Wildland",
      "Prescribed/Fuels Treatment",
      "All Hazard"
    ],
