    "snippet": "The morning of 3/16/2024 a crew member started Utility-21 which is a '2020 RAM 2500', and had started up like normal with no issues. It was cold about 30 degrees out with snow...",
    "narrative": "The morning of 3/16/2024 a crew member started Utility-21 which is a '2020 RAM 2500', and had started up like normal with no issues. It was cold about 30 degrees out with snow flurries.  We had driven it to check a prescribe burn that was in patrol status and had parked it on the shoulder of a forest service road.  After checking the burn we tried starting the truck to proceed with our day.  The truck never started, and never displayed any problem lights or warning lights on the dash.  The gauges would work but when I would press the start button with the key fob inside the truck, the truck would not start.  I tried using jumper cables, disconnecting the battery to reset the electronics, taking the key fob out of range of the truck, waited until the next day to try and start it again, nothing worked.  I called a RAM dealer to ask what the issue is and the response was 'everything you tried is what I was going to recommend doing'.  The RAM mechanic had no idea of what causes the issue of the truck not starting, knowing it is a common problem with that year, make and model of truck.",
    "immediateAction": "The truck was left on the side of the road for a 2 days before we could get it towed to a RAM dealer.  When the truck was being serviced by the RAM mechanic the battery was arching.  The mechanic said the battery, fuse and starter were all fried.  The truck never displayed any issues of not starting in the past.  Looking on forums and reading reports this is a common problem with this make and model and year of truck.  This is a real problem in the field with our work in wildland fire, with the situations we are having to be placed in and remote areas, people could be in real danger if they couldn't start this vehicle to evade the potential danger.  I personally as a Crew Supervisor won't trust this vehicle ever again being this is a common problem and the mechanics of RAM don't know the root problem of what causes this.",
    "mgmtLevel": "3",
    "task": "Checking prescribe burn in patrol status",
    "resources": "Utility-21",
